{{Wikisource1911Enc|Butlerage and Prisage}}
A '''butlerage''' was a [[Duty (economics)|duty]] of two [[shilling]]s on every ton of [[wine]] imported into [[England]] by merchant strangers; so called because it was paid to the king's butler for the king.  The tax was first implemented in 1302 and stopped being levied in 1809.<ref>Dictionary of Political Economy, Volume I, Macmillan and Co, London, 1894, p. 196</ref>

