==Broadcast history==

The show started life in 2010 as "Wasteman TV", a [[YouTube]] series that was filmed and edited by Asim Chaudhry (Chabuddy G)<ref>{{cite web
| title= People Just Do Nothing Webisodes
| publisher=Youtube
| work=Wasteman TV
| accessdate=2014-09-07
| date=2010-07-30
| url=https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLC7B9AFBA195C928F}}</ref>
before the BBC commissioned a pilot on 17 August 2012, which became the most shared [[BBC iPlayer|iPlayer]] show for the month. A four-part series was eventually commissioned, which first aired on iPlayer in July 2014, then on terrestrial television the following month.<ref>{{cite web
| title= People Just Do Nothing - from Youtube to BBC Comedy Feed to full series
| publisher=BBC Online
| accessdate=2014-09-07
| work=Writersroom Blog
| date=2014-07-14
| url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/writersroom/posts/People-Just-Do-Nothing-from-Youtube-to-BBC-Comedy-Feed-to-full-series}}</ref> A second series, of five episodes, aired in July 2015.<ref>{{cite web
| title= People Just Do Nothing gets second series on BBC Three
| accessdate=2014-12-18
| work=[[Digital Spy]]
| date=2014-11-13
| url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/news/a609795/people-just-do-nothing-gets-second-series-on-bbc-three.html}}</ref> 

In October 2015, the BBC announced it had commissioned a third and fourth series of ''People Just Do Nothing'',<ref>{{cite web
| title= Critically acclaimed mockumentary series People Just Do Nothing returns to BBC Three for third and fourth series
| publisher=BBC Online
| accessdate=2016-02-25
| work=BBC Media Centre
| date=2015-10-09
| url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2015/pjdn-three-and-four}}</ref> both consisting of six 30-minute episodes.<ref>{{cite web
| title= People Just Do Nothing wins double order
| publisher=Broadcast
| accessdate=2016-02-25
| author=Hannah Gannagé-Stewart
| date=2015-10-09
| url=http://www.broadcastnow.co.uk/news/people-just-do-nothing-wins-double-order/5095303.article}}</ref> The BBC confirmed Series 3 & 4 would initially be available on the new [[BBC Three (online)|online BBC Three]] and later screened on [[BBC Two]]. 

Episode one of series three premiered on BBC iPlayer on 17 August 2016. Episodes of series three were released weekly on iPlayer and then broadcast the following week on BBC Two. Series four began on iPlayer on 15 August 2017,<ref>{{cite news|title=People Just Do Nothing Series 4 start-date announcement|url=https://twitter.com/KuruptFM/status/887697677701586946|agency=Twitter}}</ref> and was also broadcast on [[BBC One]] on Saturday evenings.

In [[Australia]], the series premiered on 12 August 2015 on [[Channel V Australia|Channel [V]]].<ref name="Aug10Fox">{{cite web|publisher=The Green Room|first=Charles|last=Purcell|url=http://community.foxtel.com.au/t5/Foxtel-Blog/New-This-Week-Aug-10-True-Detective-finale-The-Interceptor-GOT/ba-p/86204|title=
New This Week (Aug 10): True Detective finale, The Interceptor, GOT S1-5, Graceland and live sport |date=6 August 2015|accessdate=7 August 2015|archivedate=7 August 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150807011903/http://community.foxtel.com.au/t5/Foxtel-Blog/New-This-Week-Aug-10-True-Detective-finale-The-Interceptor-GOT/ba-p/86204}}</ref> In the US, the show premiered on [[Viceland]] on February 2, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pMvQEMVgr94|title=PEOPLE JUST DO NOTHING (Series Trailer)|first=|last=VICELAND|date=21 December 2016|publisher=|accessdate=23 September 2018|via=YouTube}}</ref>. The show was also added to [[Netflix]] US in May 2017.<ref name=lat>{{cite web|title=Music-focused British series 'People Just Do Nothing' celebrates the 'idiots everywhere'|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/la-et-ms-people-just-do-nothing-netflix-bbc-20170526-story.html|website=Los Angeles Times|date=29 May 2017}}</ref>

In March 2017 the cast appeared alongside musician [[Ed Sheeran]] in a spoof music video for the charity [[Comic Relief]] on [[BBC One]].  

===Home media===

The DVD of the first three series was released in November 2016. The boxset included specially recorded commentaries from the first two series and unseen extra footage.

